    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Dear Editor, Experts have predicted a ''tsunami of psychiatric illness'' in the aftermath of COVID-19 pandemic (Tandon; . For such a large scale event like COVID-19 pandemic, the impact on mental health can be long lasting (Galea et al; .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 93,
                    "end": 119,
                    "text": "COVID-19 pandemic (Tandon;",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 223,
                    "end": 236,
                    "text": "(Galea et al;",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "The prevalence of common mental health disorders is expected to rise during the post-pandemic time as a result of the long term effects of the pandemic, the restrictive measures such as social distancing and quarantine and the socioeconomic effects. This has implications for mental health services.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "People experience emotional disturbance, irritability, insomnia, depression and post-traumatic stress symptoms immediately after the quarantine period. The long term impact is considerable and wide ranging including anxiety, anger, depression, post-traumatic stress symptoms, alcohol abuse, and behavioural changes such as avoiding crowded places and cautious hand washing. These psychological symptoms can last from several months up to three years after the quarantine period (Brooks et al; .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 478,
                    "end": 492,
                    "text": "(Brooks et al;",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental health impact of quarantine and social distancing:"
        },
        {
            "text": "Social distancing could possibly lead to substantial increases in loneliness, anxiety, depression, domestic violence, child abuse and substance abuse (Galea et al; .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 150,
                    "end": 163,
                    "text": "(Galea et al;",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental health impact of quarantine and social distancing:"
        },
        {
            "text": "Prolonged social isolation can lead to social withdrawal, a phenomenon known as Hikikomori, which may further be aggravated by the economic and social crisis of the pandemic. Although Covid-19 related social isolation appears to be similar to Hikikomori, there are differences between the two conditions as Covid-19 social J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f isolation is imposed by governments and also stems from the individuals' avoidance behavior due to the fear of infection (Kato et al; .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 475,
                    "end": 487,
                    "text": "(Kato et al;",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental health impact of quarantine and social distancing:"
        },
        {
            "text": "In patients who required hospitalization following COVID-19, delirium is common during the acute stage of the illness. The data on long term psychiatric complications in these group of patients, although not yet fully known, may be comparable to previous corona virus epidemics, severe acute respiratory (SARS) and Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) with increased prevalence of anxiety, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 304,
                    "end": 310,
                    "text": "(SARS)",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental health issues after Covid-19 recovery:"
        },
        {
            "text": "Persistent psychiatric impairment with significant levels of anxiety, depression and post-traumatic stress disorder are seen in survivors of critical illness at 1 year after discharge. Neurocognitive impairment including impaired attention, concentration, memory, and mental processing speed at 1 year was found in majority of patients with severe acute respiratory distress syndrome. Substantial reductions in quality of life were found in patients with severe acute respiratory syndrome and prolonged mechanical ventilation after discharge from intensive care unit compared to admissions for other reasons (Rogers et al; .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 608,
                    "end": 622,
                    "text": "(Rogers et al;",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF17"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental health issues after Covid-19 recovery:"
        },
        {
            "text": "Psychological symptoms including anxiety, depression, insomnia are prevalent in up to 60% among physicians, nurses and medical residents during Post-traumatic stress symptoms were reported by 11% to 73% of HCP during epidemic or pandemic outbreaks that lasted in up to 10 to 40% after 1-3 years (Preti et al; .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 295,
                    "end": 308,
                    "text": "(Preti et al;",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF16"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental health impact on frontline healthcare professionals (HCP):"
        },
        {
            "text": "World Bank has predicted steep global economic recession since decades following the COVID-19 pandemic. This may adversely impact on mental health especially of the vulnerable groups.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Post COVID-19 economic recession, social inequalities and impact on mental health:"
        },
        {
            "text": "Economic recession has been associated with increases in the prevalence of psychological distress, anxiety, depression, substance abuse disorders, and suicide and suicidal behavior. Unemployment, insecure job situation, lower socioeconomic status, and pre-existing psychiatric problems seem to be the determinants of post-economic recession mental health issues (Frasquilho et al, 2020) .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 362,
                    "end": 386,
                    "text": "(Frasquilho et al, 2020)",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Post COVID-19 economic recession, social inequalities and impact on mental health:"
        },
        {
            "text": "Unemployment following economic recession is a major risk factor for suicide and suicide rates had considerably increased following global economic crisis in 2008 (Chang et al, 2013) . A potential economic recession with rise in unemployment following Covid-19 pandemic might have similar impact on suicide rate.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 163,
                    "end": 182,
                    "text": "(Chang et al, 2013)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Post COVID-19 economic recession, social inequalities and impact on mental health:"
        },
        {
            "text": "J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f Stigma against HCP and survivors of the COVID-19 infection has resulted in harassment, stereotyping, discrimination, social isolation, and in some instances physical violence (Bagcchi, 2020) . Stigmatised individuals may experience emotional disturbance, anxiety, depression and emotional disturbance (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 2020).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 206,
                    "end": 221,
                    "text": "(Bagcchi, 2020)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Stigma related to Covid-19 pandemic:"
        },
        {
            "text": "The mental health impact of the COVID-19 pandemic can persist and be long lasting for several years after the pandemic. Increases in the prevalence of common psychiatric disorders and suicide are expected during the postpandemic time. Enhancing access to the mental health services including telepsychiatry, early assessment, treatment and psycho-social support, screening and support for specific groups such as frontline HCP where appropriate, implementing long term measures to mitigate the impact of economic recession on mental health and addressing stigma during the pandemic are paramount in addressing the problem.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Conclusion:"
        },
        {
            "text": "COVID-19; Quarantine, Social distancing, Mental health impact; Suicide; Mental health services",
